<section xml:id="section-assignment4">
  <title>Assignment 4</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      Solve this differential equation using Laplace transforms. (6) 
      <md>
        <mrow>
          y^{\prime \prime} + 4y^{\prime} + 3y \amp = u_{\pi}(t) \sin
          t
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          y(0) \amp = 0
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          y^\prime(0) \amp = 1
        </mrow>
      </md>
    </li>
    <li>
      Solve this differential equation using Laplace transforms. (6) 
      <md>
        <mrow>
          y^{\prime \prime} + y^{\prime} + 7y \amp = 3 + 3 \delta_4(t) 
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          y(0) \amp = 3
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          y^\prime(0) \amp = 0
        </mrow>
      </md>
    </li>
    <li>
      Solve this differential equation using Laplace transforms. (6) 
      <md>
        <mrow>
          y^{\prime \prime} + 2y^{\prime} + y \amp = \delta_1(t) +
          \delta_2(t) + \delta_3(t)
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          y(0) \amp = 0
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          y^\prime(0) \amp = 1
        </mrow>
      </md>
    </li>
    <li>
      Solve this differential equation using Laplace transforms. (6) 
      <md>
        <mrow>
          y^{\prime \prime} + y^{\prime} + y \amp = e^t \sinh t
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          y(0) \amp = 0
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          y^\prime(0) \amp = 1
        </mrow>
      </md>
    </li>
    <li>
      Solve these two differential equations.
      <md>
        <mrow>
          y^{\prime \prime} + 4y^{\prime} + 4y \amp = 0
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          y(0) \amp = 0
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          y^\prime(0) \amp = 4
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          y^{\prime \prime} + 4y^{\prime} + 4y \amp = 4\delta_0(t) 
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          y(0) \amp = 0
        </mrow>
        <mrow>
          y^\prime(0) \amp = 0
        </mrow>
      </md>
      Explain the connection between the two equations. (8) 
    </li>
    <li>
      Consider the following odd claim about distributions.
      <me>
        \frac{d}{dt} u_a(t) = \delta_a(t)
      </me>
      Explain why this might possibly be true. Then apply the Laplace
      transform to the equation to show that, at least after the
      transform, both sides of the equation are equal. (6)
    </li>
    <li>
      Describe the behaviour you expect out of an overdamped system
      forced by a square wave? You can answer qualitatively or
      quantitatively, with explanations or calculations, but you  must
      give reasons for the behaviour you predict. (6) 
    </li>
  </ol></p>
</section>
